</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA53C58FF6BB81FFA1384C2" blockId="3.[151,1437,1610,2033]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="242" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">
This species was described from 
<specimenCount id="9D4C12D0FFA53C5FFDF5B81FFD098272" box="[521,671,1611,1637]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" type="female">three females</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="9D4C12D0FFA53C5FFD29B81FFCCE8272" box="[725,856,1611,1637]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" type="male">three males</specimenCount>
, taken in 
<collectingCountry id="F35D99C9FFA53C5FFC3FB81FFBE68272" box="[963,1136,1611,1637]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
at Bois du Sud, 
<date id="FFF4FF99FFA53C5FFAD4B81FFA0E8272" box="[1320,1432,1610,1637]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" value="1950-07">July 1950</date>
, from the rolled leaves of an undetermined plant. The descriptive notes below are based on the 
<typeStatus id="54F167FBFFA53C5FFB4AB83BFA8E829E" box="[1206,1304,1647,1673]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">holotype</typeStatus>
female that was studied in Canberra, on loan from the Bishop Museum, Hawaii. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFBF1B8C7FB3D82BA" authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1919" box="[1037,1195,1683,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Arrhenothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFBF1B8C7FB3D82BA" box="[1037,1195,1683,1709]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Arrhenothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDBA4A8FFA53C5FFAA2B8C7FF7482C6" author="Hood" firstAuthor="Hood" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" pagination="90 - 103" refId="ref3456" refString="Hood, J. D. (1919) On some new Thysanoptera from southern India. Insecutor inscitiae menstruus, 7, 90 - 103." type="journal article" year="1919">Hood (1919)</bibRefCitation>
for a single species that he described from 
<collectingCountry id="F35D99C9FFA53C5FFD43B8E3FD6F82C6" box="[703,761,1719,1745]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">India</collectingCountry>
as 
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFCE0B8E3FC2E82C6" box="[796,952,1719,1745]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">ramakrishnae</emphasis>
. That species has the typical antennal sense cone formula of members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFDECB88FFDE182E2" authorityName="Uzel" authorityYear="1895" box="[528,631,1755,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Liothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFDECB88FFDE182E2" box="[528,631,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Liothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lineage, 1 on III, 3 on IV, but both sexes have a stout fore tarsal tooth and females have the fore femora enlarged. However, the relationships of this genus require further study, including a further four species from 
<collectingCountry id="F35D99C9FFA53C5FFE09B977FDB9832A" box="[501,559,1827,1853]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">India</collectingCountry>
and two from Africa that were subsequently included (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDBA4A8FFA53C5FFB64B977FAC8832A" accessDate="2021-07-08" author="ThripsWiki" box="[1176,1374,1827,1853]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" publicationUrl="http://thrips.info/wiki/" refId="ref3836" refString="ThripsWiki (2021) ThripsWiki - providing information on the World's thrips. Available from: http: // thrips. info / wiki / (accessed 8 July 2021)" title="ThripsWiki - providing information on the World's thrips" type="url" year="2021">ThripsWiki 2021</bibRefCitation>
). The species considered here from 
<collectingCountry id="F35D99C9FFA53C5FFE19B913FD058376" box="[485,659,1863,1889]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
seems unrelated to 
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFC8FB913FB998376" box="[883,1039,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">ramakrishnae</emphasis>
in having two stout sense cones on antennal segments III and IV, and antennal segment VIII elongate and narrowed to the base. Moreover, contrary to the description by Bianchi, the fore femora are not particularly enlarged, and the fore tibial inner apex is simple and does not have “a broad tubercle-like distal production” (
<figureCitation id="1371C5DCFFA53C5FFCE5B9E7FCC983DA" box="[793,863,1971,1997]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,237,1705]" captionTargetId="figure-57@4.[151,1435,237,1708]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Teuchothrips and Neocecidothrips. (5) T. ornatus head (LAM5607). N. pacificus holotype 6–12: (6) head; (7) fore tibia &amp; tarsus; (8) antenna; (9) mesonotum, metanotum &amp; pelta. (10) head &amp; pronotum; (11) pronotum; (12) prosternum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6405148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6405148/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). The elongate antennal segment VIII of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFACBB9E7FA0A83DA" authorityName="Bianchi" authorityYear="1952" box="[1335,1436,1971,1997]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Arrhenothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFACBB9E7FA0A83DA" box="[1335,1436,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="1371C5DCFFA53C5FFF5CB983FF7483E6" box="[160,226,2007,2033]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,237,1705]" captionTargetId="figure-57@4.[151,1435,237,1708]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Teuchothrips and Neocecidothrips. (5) T. ornatus head (LAM5607). N. pacificus holotype 6–12: (6) head; (7) fore tibia &amp; tarsus; (8) antenna; (9) mesonotum, metanotum &amp; pelta. (10) head &amp; pronotum; (11) pronotum; (12) prosternum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6405148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6405148/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFE82B983FD8083E6" box="[382,534,2007,2033]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Litotetothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFE82B983FD8083E6" box="[382,534,2007,2033]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Litotetothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDBA4A8FFA53C5FFD80B983FCFE83E6" author="Mound &amp; Tree" box="[636,872,2007,2033]" firstAuthor="Mound" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" pagination="445 - 450" refId="ref3732" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Tree, D. J. (2021) Litotetothrips Priesner (Thysanoptera, Phlaeothripinae); an Asian genus newly recorded from Australia with two new species and one new combination. Zootaxa, 5027 (3), 445 - 450. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5027.3.10" type="journal article" year="2021">Mound &amp; Tree 2021</bibRefCitation>
), but the maxillary stylets are deeply retracted and close together (
<figureCitation id="1371C5DCFFA23C58FEBDBEC3FE1284A5" box="[321,388,151,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,237,1705]" captionTargetId="figure-57@4.[151,1435,237,1708]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Teuchothrips and Neocecidothrips. (5) T. ornatus head (LAM5607). N. pacificus holotype 6–12: (6) head; (7) fore tibia &amp; tarsus; (8) antenna; (9) mesonotum, metanotum &amp; pelta. (10) head &amp; pronotum; (11) pronotum; (12) prosternum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6405148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6405148/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). The species is here referred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA23C58FD15BEC3FC3784A6" authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1928" box="[745,929,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Neocecidothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FD15BEC3FC3784A6" box="[745,929,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">Neocecidothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, because the two known species of that genus (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDBA4A8FFA23C58FF63BEEFFEA484C2" author="Mound" box="[159,306,187,213]" firstAuthor="Mound" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" pagination="41 - 60" refId="ref3509" refString="Mound, L. A. (2008) Identification and host associations of some Thysanoptera Phlaeothripinae described from Australia pre- 1930. Zootaxa, 1714 (1), 41 - 60. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1714.1.5" type="journal article" year="2008">Mound 2008</bibRefCitation>
) are the only members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA23C58FD7DBEEFFC8484C2" baseAuthorityName="ThripsWiki" baseAuthorityYear="2021" box="[641,786,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FD7DBEEFFC8484C2" box="[641,786,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">Teuchothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group that share a similar antennal sense cone formula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF3589D1FFA23C58FF6BB897FA1882E8" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6405148" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6405148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6405148/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" startId="4.[151,264,1731,1755]" targetBox="[151,1432,237,1705]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA23C58FF6BB897FA1882E8" blockId="4.[151,1436,1731,1791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FF6BB897FED782CC" bold="true" box="[151,321,1731,1755]" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">FIGURES 5–12</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA23C58FEB1B897FE4682CC" baseAuthorityName="ThripsWiki" baseAuthorityYear="2021" box="[333,464,1731,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FEB1B897FE4682CC" box="[333,464,1731,1755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">Teuchothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA23C58FDFDB897FD3182CC" authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1928" box="[513,679,1731,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Neocecidothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FDFDB897FD3182CC" box="[513,679,1731,1755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">Neocecidothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FD4FB897FD4782CC" bold="true" box="[691,721,1731,1755]" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">(5)</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA23C58FD2BB890FCAA82CC" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1993" box="[727,828,1732,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FD2BB890FCAA82CC" box="[727,828,1732,1755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">T. ornatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
head (LAM5607). 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA23C58FBFDB890FBEF82CC" authorityName="Bianchi" authorityYear="1952" box="[1025,1145,1731,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Arrhenothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FBFDB890FBEF82CC" box="[1025,1145,1731,1755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">N. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
holotype 6–12: 
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FAE2B897FAAA82CC" bold="true" box="[1310,1340,1731,1755]" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">(6)</emphasis>
head; 
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FA83B897FA0A82CC" bold="true" box="[1407,1436,1731,1755]" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">(7)</emphasis>
fore tibia &amp; tarsus; 
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA23C58FEA0B8B3FEEC82E8" bold="true" box="[348,378,1767,1791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="242">(8)</emphasis>
